],"variants":[{"name":"Moulton","meanings":["English (mainly Cheshire and Lancashire): habitational name from one or more of the places called Moulton (Cheshire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, Northamptonshire, Staffordshire, Suffolk, North Yorkshire), most of which are named with the Old English personal name <i>Mūl(a)</i>, the Old Norse personal name <i>Múli</i>, or Old English <i>mūl</i> ‘mule’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Multon II of Gilsland was born about 1250, in Gilsland, Northumberland, England, his father, Thomas de Moulton I of Gilsland, was 26 and his mother, Maude de Vaux, was 27. He had at least 1 son with Helewisa Levington. He died in 1293, in his hometown, at the age of 44."},"et":{"about 1250–1293":"umbes 1250–1293","1240–1268":"1240–1268","1250–1293":"1250–1293","1254–1300":"1254–1300",